meet e4 with Na6.} Bb7 9. e4 (9. b3 Nbd7 10. Bb2 Rc8 11. e4 c5 $13 {With an
extremely unclear position.}) 9... Na6 $1 {With this unusual knight
development, we gain a nice position as we have the option of bringing our
knight back to d7 if White plays e5.}) 8... Nbd7 $1 {Once White has put the
rook on d1, we need to keep the option open of developing the bishop on b7 or
a6. Hence first Nbd7 is a better move.} 9. Bf4 (9. b3 Ba6 10. Nc3 (10. Nbd2 c5
{Also leads to very sharp lines.}) 10... dxc4 $5 {With an extremely
